Getting started with connectivity modeling

Matt Williamson

3/4/2021

What are we connecting?

Any connectivity modeling exercise begins with deciding what (or where) we are hoping to connect. This can be (and often is) protected areas, suitable (or good) habitat, known home ranges, etc. In the context of circuit theory, we might call these the nodes or the vertices of the graph. They comprise the portion of the network we are interested in connecting. In order to make this exercise computationally efficient, well use GAP1 status protected areas in Wyoming (US) that are larger than 50000 ac (~20000 ha). Well load those here:

prot.areas <- st_read("Data/wy_gap1.shp")
## Reading layer `wy_gap1' from data source `/Users/mattwilliamson/Courses/restistutorial/Data/wy_gap1.shp' using driver `ESRI Shapefile'
## Simple feature collection with 13 features and 33 fields
## geometry type:  MULTIPOLYGON
## dimension:      XY
## bbox:           xmin: -1205283 ymin: 642320.3 xmax: -872425.3 ymax: 932786.6
## projected CRS:  USA_Contiguous_Albers_Equal_Area_Conic
plot(st_geometry(prot.areas))

There are several additional considerations for how we want to represent these in the network: 1. We can use the entirety of the patch 2. We can use the centroid of the patch 3. We can choose random points within the patches

Well do that here:

node.cent <- st_centroid(prot.areas)
## Warning in st_centroid.sf(prot.areas): st_centroid assumes attributes are
## constant over geometries of x
node.sample <- st_sample(prot.areas, size= rep(1, nrow(prot.areas)))

What are the impediments?

Resistance surfaces depict the degree of difficulty (and/or likelihood of mortality) an animal experiences moving across the landscape. This difficulty might simply be a function of Euclidean distance or may be a complex set of interactions between a variety of biophysical and social factors. For simplicitys sake, we are only going to consider two elements here: slope and human modification.

hm <- raster('Data/human_mod.tif')
plot(hm)

elev <- raster('Data/elevation_agg.tif')
slope <- terrain(elev, opt='slope', unit = 'degrees')

A brief note about functional form

sim.res <- rnorm(1000)
lin.res <- sim.res
exp.up <- exp(sim.res)
exp.dn <- exp(-sim.res)

In order to use these data in Circuitscape (or Omniscape), we need to convert these points into categorical rasters.

#patch.based.node <- fasterize::fasterize(prot.areas, field = "OBJECTID")
